article.headline: Wyoming 83, BYU 71
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- After an embarrassing 25-point loss to Utah on its home floor two days earlier, Wyoming was hoping to make amends against rival Brigham Young. "We felt like we let the whole state down how we played Saturday," senior Dion Sherrell said. "We tried to come back today and tried to get the love back." The love is back after Sherrell and Justin Williams each scored 19 points in leading Wyoming past BYU 83-71 Monday night and handing the Cougars their fourth loss in the last five games. Sherrell said the victory over BYU helped the team rebound from a 74-49 loss to Utah on Saturday -- a loss that hurt all the more because Wyoming celebrated its 100th year of basketball during the game. "The way we played today, and if we can continue to keep going hard in practice and keep pushing ourselves, the sky is the limit," he said. Wyoming (9-7 overall, 1-2 Mountain West) trailed only once against BYU -- in the first half -- but managed a 35-31 halftime lead. BYU tied the game early in the second half with an 8-4 run, only to see Wyoming build a pair of eight-point leads. The Cougars worked back to within 59-57 on a 3-pointer by Mike Hall, but Wyoming answered with a 10-4 run started by a 3-point-play by Williams, followed by a 3-point shot by Sherrell. BYU would get no closer than 69-65 with 5:49 to go after back-to-back baskets by Derek Dawes. Wyoming outscored the Cougars 14-6 the rest of the way, with Derek Wabbington scoring eight of the points. "It's the same thing when you play just good enough to lose, and I am pretty much sick of it," BYU coach Steve Cleveland said. "They're the ones that have to step up, and I can't do anymore." The Cowboys, who had lost four of their last six entering the game, also got 14 points from Jay Straight, 12 from Wabbington and 10 from Alex Dunn. BYU (6-12, 0-3) was led by Hall's 16 points. Mike Rose added 13, Dawes 11 and Keena Young 10.
